<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-03-22T00:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-03-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="659" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d659">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01 Manchuria/63: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="#p_JNT1" type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-03-22T13:00:00+08:00">March 22, 1932—1
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 22—3:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>361. Following from Reuter, Tokyo, March 21st: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“Acknowledging the Manchurian government’s note of March 12th but
                                    making no reference to the question of recognition, the Japanese
                                    Government today sent a communication through the Japanese
                                    Consul <pb facs="0722" n="618" xml:id="pg_618"/> at Changchun
                                    welcoming the new state’s declared policy of the open door,
                                    equal opportunity and respect for existing
                                treaties.”</p></quote></p>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><persName><hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>